ractices which introduces a mild negative sentiment tempered by societal awareness.\n\n- Impacts in Asia (0 Very Negative): The document presents alarming statistics on air pollution levels exacerbated by climate change and its disproportionate impact on vulnerable populations, with little to no mention of successful mitigation efforts or policy responses which results in a very negative sentiment due to the absence of any positive aspects.\n\n- Impacts in Africa (1 Mildly Negative): While it acknowledges that climate change is causing severe drought and food security issues across many African nations, there are also mentions of grassroots movements pushing for environmental justice which provides a mild negative sentiment with an undercurrent of hopeful resistance.\n\n- Mitigation Strategies in Europe (4 Very Positive): The document details ambitious climate action plans like the European Green Deal and significant investments into renewable energy, suggesting strong optimism about their potential to combat climate change effectively which results in a very positive sentiment due to clear progressive steps being taken.\n\n- Mitigation Strategies in North America (3 Mildly Positive): It discusses the advancements made by countries like Canada and Mexico towards reducing carbon emissions, but also notes that these efforts are not yet enough which imparts a mild positive sentiment as it acknowledges progress while recognizing there is still much work to be done.\n\n- Mitigation Strategies in Asia (2 Neutral): The document presents both the challenges faced by rapidly industrializing nations and their commitments under international agreements, creating an overall neutral tone due to a balance between current struggles with climate change impacts and ongoing efforts for sustainable development.\n\n- Mitigation Strategies in Africa (3 Mildly Positive): Despite the continent's vulnerability to climate change effects like desertification, there are mentions of increasing